WEBVTT

00:02.178 --> 00:16.454
From Genesis chapter 49, verse 8 through 12, Judah, your brothers shall praise you.

00:18.376 --> 00:20.939
Your hands shall be on the neck of your enemies.

00:21.640 --> 00:24.583
Your father's son shall bow down before you.

00:26.044 --> 00:27.606
Judah is a lion's cub.

00:28.908 --> 00:31.090
From the prey, my son, you have gone up.

00:31.746 --> 00:38.093
He stooped down, he crouched as a lion, and as a lioness, who dares rouse him.

00:39.054 --> 00:49.926
The scepter shall not depart from Judah, nor the ruler's staff from between his feet, until tribute comes to him, and to him shall be the obedience of the peoples.

00:51.688 --> 00:56.914
Buying in his fold to the vine, in his donkey's colt, to the choice vine,

00:58.146 --> 01:03.573
He has washed his garments and wine and his vesture in the blood of grapes.

01:05.515 --> 01:10.801
His eyes are darker than wine, and his teeth wider than milk.

01:12.143 --> 01:18.791
The grass withers and the flowers fade, but the word of our God will stand forever, and may he be seated.

01:22.235 --> 01:25.199
Pray with me, merciful God in heaven.

01:26.600 --> 01:28.082
We give you thanks for your word.

01:29.058 --> 01:43.174
When your words like this that seem mysterious and confusing, I pray that your spirit would speak to us, that you would encourage and strengthen our hearts as we consider and meditate on your holy word.

01:43.775 --> 01:50.002
But you give to your people not to confuse us, but that we might find life and truth in you.

01:51.063 --> 01:57.010
I pray that you'd help us accomplish this morning in your name we pray, amen.

01:58.626 --> 02:12.467
You know, there are certain moments in life when all the broken things of this world kind of fade into the background and you just experience beauty, glory, joy.

02:12.527 --> 02:17.474
I think one of those moments for a lot of people can be when they get married.

02:18.276 --> 02:25.106
It's this transcendent moment before these people and there's feasting, there's joy, there's laughter.

02:25.282 --> 02:38.484
You're not the one getting married when you get to attend a wedding and you know the people well and it's this joyous moment and kind of the pains in life kind of fade away for a second and you just get to experience joy and beauty.

02:40.286 --> 02:45.094
But anyone who's been married knows that marriage is more than just a moment of a wedding.

02:45.154 --> 02:49.842
It's life together.

02:50.306 --> 02:56.634
And pretty soon you move, go from this wedding feast to ordinary life, an ordinary life with anybody is challenging.

02:57.656 --> 03:01.281
And oftentimes when I'll do premarital counseling, I warn people of this truth.

03:01.321 --> 03:04.425
I'll tell them, hey, the weddings are awesome.

03:04.445 --> 03:05.727
Enjoy every moment of it.

03:06.588 --> 03:07.168
Just soak it up.

03:07.489 --> 03:09.011
Even if things don't go right, it's fine.

03:09.992 --> 03:10.853
No one will remember that.

03:14.058 --> 03:17.362
But just so you know, the day after,

03:17.538 --> 03:18.239
It can be hard.

03:18.399 --> 03:20.322
That evening can be difficult for you.

03:20.842 --> 03:25.468
As soon as you move from like this wedding feast to just life together, it can be challenging.

03:25.488 --> 03:29.453
And oftentimes the first fights, big fights happen on the honeymoon.

03:29.774 --> 03:34.339
From the ordinary things of like, oh, this is how you squeeze your toothpaste tube?

03:34.600 --> 03:36.242
I was like, I don't like that.

03:36.682 --> 03:37.864
Wish that would have come up earlier.

03:37.904 --> 03:45.874
So the whole toilet seat thing, to the way they chew their food, to the way they load their dishes, which, you know, there's all right and wrong ways to load dishwashers.

03:46.018 --> 03:49.984
And you discover your spouse does it the wrong way, you know, pretty quick in the marriage.

03:50.725 --> 03:55.572
And so it doesn't take long for that bliss of marriage to turn into irritation.

03:55.612 --> 04:00.339
And I think this is a kind of a microcosm of how we experience life.

04:01.260 --> 04:10.514
Life in general, moments of beauty, moments of transcendence, moments where love kind of breaks in, moments where there's joy and glory.

04:10.850 --> 04:14.955
where you experience the kindness of somebody, even just the beauty of the sunset and the glory of creation.

04:14.995 --> 04:21.962
There's these moments in life where all your, the pains and sorrows that we experience all the time can kind of fade into the background.

04:24.705 --> 04:30.171
But on this side of a sunset is darkness and this side of joy can be pain, disappointment, resentment.

04:31.933 --> 04:37.399
Like the, the beauty that we experience in this life is that kind of thing that you, you can't like fully grasp.

04:38.120 --> 04:39.922
It's the vapor, it's mist that you can,

04:40.066 --> 05:02.034
You can have for a moment, but it's just a moment and you experience the frustration of living life in this kind of world of a world where there is an innate brokenness that touches everything, that our world is utterly tainted with the sin of Adam, which is our sin as well.

05:02.978 --> 05:14.154
like this disobedience of God that impacts every part of life from our own hearts to our relationships with others, to even the creation that we live in, everything is a war with itself.

05:14.174 --> 05:18.220
And Genesis is this book as we come to the end that tells the story of our world.

05:18.300 --> 05:23.888
It tells you how this world got to be problematic for us.

05:25.070 --> 05:27.794
And not just like where this problem comes from,

05:28.258 --> 05:36.569
But also, because we're born in the image of God, it tells us why we're so frustrated with the world the way it is, because we know it's not supposed to be so frustrating.

05:37.350 --> 05:40.875
It's not supposed to be so hard, but yet it is, because the sin is into the world.

05:41.355 --> 05:43.538
But the story doesn't stop there, even from the beginning.

05:43.558 --> 05:52.410
In Genesis 3, when the curse gets spoken to humanity, to Adam and Eve, we also get a profound promise.

05:53.011 --> 05:55.314
Not only does Genesis tell us the problem with this world,

05:55.650 --> 06:00.918
And our frustration with this world, where that comes from, but it also tells us solution is that one will come.

06:02.521 --> 06:04.564
One will come and he will crush the head of the serpent.

06:04.604 --> 06:07.989
He will free this world of all its darkness.

06:09.852 --> 06:11.114
He will renew all things.

06:11.254 --> 06:12.957
This serpent crusher is coming.

06:15.140 --> 06:24.274
And that promise that was in Genesis three, that Missy on the promise is actually picked up again here in Genesis chapter 49.

06:25.186 --> 06:36.517
In many ways, the book of Genesis is bookended with this messianic promise that God has not forgotten His promise to bring about the renewal of all things.

06:38.339 --> 06:46.246
He's still bringing about that future and now it's narrowed down its lens showing us that future is actually going to come through Judah.

06:47.948 --> 06:52.092
The last messianic promise here at the end of Genesis, God has not forgotten.

06:52.953 --> 06:54.034
He will renew

06:54.114 --> 06:56.897
our broken world, he will crush Satan.

06:58.299 --> 07:16.722
And this will happen through Judah and his family, which already shows us that this is, I mean, this is, Genesis chapter 49 is particularly a challenging chapter to understand, but this one point that everyone agrees on in chapter 49 is that this is messianic.

07:16.742 --> 07:19.666
This section we just read is all about the one, not Judah,

07:19.938 --> 07:21.761
It's talking about things that he couldn't possibly accomplish.

07:21.781 --> 07:25.186
It's about the one that's gonna come through the line of Judah, which is Jesus himself.

07:27.389 --> 07:36.723
The God is gonna fulfill his promise to Eve that he will crush the serpent, that he will end sins tyranny in our world, bringing lasting joy.

07:36.743 --> 07:38.125
This is our hope.

07:39.187 --> 07:49.202
So as we dive into this morning, for many of you, if not most of you, if not all of you, what I'm gonna say this morning won't be particularly new for you.

07:50.562 --> 08:02.158
But there are things that we need to constantly keep reminding ourselves of, that hope does win, that sin does not win, that glory, that beauty of Christ will endure forever.

08:02.198 --> 08:07.565
And so this morning, we're going to meditate on the person of Jesus.

08:07.806 --> 08:13.874
And what this tells us about Jesus, that how can Jesus do all these things and renew this world because of who He is?

08:14.402 --> 08:21.113
And there's three aspects of the nature of Christ that I think that this points to, that we need to help renew our hopes in our own day.

08:21.133 --> 08:22.215
And there are these.

08:23.237 --> 08:24.298
One, that Jesus is God.

08:26.061 --> 08:28.385
Second, that Jesus is the Lion King God.

08:28.405 --> 08:34.115
And third, that Jesus is God, the crucified Lion King.

08:35.056 --> 08:38.121
And so, if you're a note taker, you could just write the last sentence down.

08:38.161 --> 08:40.946
I'm kinda just building on that one sentence, adding

08:41.282 --> 08:46.990
fun adjectives along the way but the final word being Jesus is God the crucified Lion King.

08:48.752 --> 08:57.043
So first as we consider how this reveals who Jesus is the first thing we discover is that Jesus the one who's coming that this is pointing to is God.

08:58.064 --> 08:59.246
Jesus is God.

09:00.828 --> 09:08.498
Again as a side note just to point out many commentators will say that Genesis 49 is not only

09:08.802 --> 09:17.336
the most difficult chapter to understand in Genesis or in the Old Testament, which if you've ever read like Isaiah or Jeremiah, you know there's lots of confusing parts of the Old Testament.

09:18.838 --> 09:24.647
People will say this is the most challenging chapter in all of scripture to fully understand its poetic nature.

09:24.727 --> 09:28.373
Some of the things that brings up, it's the first time they're brought up in scriptures.

09:29.535 --> 09:36.466
And it's about this kind of near prophetic promise to Judah and his family, but it's also

09:36.578 --> 09:39.181
fulfillment that's going to be carried out generations later.

09:39.562 --> 09:42.265
So there's all sorts of layers and imagery happening here.

09:43.146 --> 09:53.839
But there are a few things that are very clear, like I mentioned, that this section is about Jesus, the one that's going to come through the line of Judah.

09:53.959 --> 09:58.304
It's about this messianic promise that there is a Messiah that's going to come.

09:58.324 --> 10:00.587
It's going to rescue and redeem his people.

10:00.667 --> 10:02.930
And this Messiah is not an ordinary person.

10:03.671 --> 10:06.354
He's not just another prophet in the line, but he is

10:06.850 --> 10:07.311
divine.

10:08.072 --> 10:09.394
And we see that here right at the beginning.

10:09.434 --> 10:15.022
This verse 8 says, Judah, your brothers shall praise you.

10:16.625 --> 10:23.675
So this word praise here is not an ordinary kind of praising like, hey, you did a really good job.

10:25.458 --> 10:26.179
Good job, buddy.

10:26.640 --> 10:27.701
It's not that kind of praise.

10:27.741 --> 10:36.114
This is a word that's actually reserved nearly exclusively, like 99.9% of the time it's reserved for the person

10:36.290 --> 10:38.393
for God himself, for Yahweh.

10:39.154 --> 10:41.518
This is not a word it's used for humans.

10:42.119 --> 10:48.309
Sure, Judah does become the prominent tribe amongst his kin.

10:48.990 --> 10:51.533
His kingdom is the strongest and longest lasting.

10:52.455 --> 11:02.290
But this is clearly speaking to more than just that, as this is a word reserved for God, this is poetically saying, listen, not Judah, you are God.

11:03.106 --> 11:11.897
But it's poetically telling us that one will come from your line, who is God, who is, who is praised like goddess, who carries a messianic promise.

11:11.937 --> 11:17.965
Even the temptation of Jesus that was just read earlier, you saw that God alone can have glory and honor and praise and worship.

11:18.005 --> 11:19.507
This is what this is talking about.

11:20.148 --> 11:28.178
That worship is going to come for a descendant of Judah, who is worthy of praise because he is God.

11:31.522 --> 11:38.273
This is the messianic promise coming to the future showing us that the one that's going to come in the line of Judah is God himself.

11:38.734 --> 11:41.478
And you see this again that the father's sons bow down.

11:42.440 --> 11:43.762
Again, that's worship language.

11:44.363 --> 11:45.725
And it's doing a couple of things for one.

11:45.765 --> 11:50.674
I think in our heads it brings up this Joseph dreams kind of resurfacing that Joseph has said his brothers would bow down to him.

11:50.694 --> 11:55.221
But this is in the context of this praise, this divine worship kind of praise.

11:56.082 --> 11:58.226
This is deeper than what happened to Joseph.

11:58.498 --> 12:09.717
And we see this kind of developing here throughout the end when we see like all these nations and tribes are going to come and obey and bow down and praise this descendant.

12:11.500 --> 12:12.101
This is big.

12:12.141 --> 12:12.702
It's global.

12:12.722 --> 12:13.523
It's about worship.

12:14.906 --> 12:16.188
Let's reserve for God himself.

12:16.208 --> 12:19.554
This is saying that that's going to happen to the one that comes from your line, Judah.

12:20.375 --> 12:22.098
And remember,

12:22.690 --> 12:26.394
Jacob's blessings to his sons are not just ordinary blessings that you might give.

12:26.434 --> 12:31.579
If you knew you were about to die, they'd call your children next to you and say, hey, man, the Lord be with you and also with you.

12:32.059 --> 12:33.481
This isn't like those kind of blessings.

12:33.641 --> 12:34.942
This is prophetic.

12:35.062 --> 12:37.545
He's telling them what their future will be.

12:38.826 --> 12:39.667
This is not a maybe.

12:39.787 --> 12:41.248
I hope you have a good life.

12:41.769 --> 12:43.070
There's a few hundred bucks.

12:43.711 --> 12:46.153
This is, no, this is your future.

12:48.095 --> 12:51.218
And actually, we see this clearly pointing to Jesus, I think,

12:51.842 --> 12:53.564
and his triumphal entry on Palm Sunday.

12:54.105 --> 13:01.836
Already some of the imagery in here might have made you think about Palm Sunday when Jesus rides into Jerusalem the week before his crucifixion.

13:03.778 --> 13:04.620
And people, what do they do?

13:04.660 --> 13:05.320
They praise him.

13:05.341 --> 13:09.066
They lay down palms and they lay down their cloaks in front of him.

13:09.086 --> 13:10.007
He is riding what?

13:10.568 --> 13:11.048
A donkey.

13:11.068 --> 13:14.453
And you get some of this imagery in here that you see a donkey here.

13:14.934 --> 13:17.717
And that image of the donkey actually grows throughout the Old Testament.

13:17.737 --> 13:21.042
You find kings riding donkeys to the coronation.

13:21.410 --> 13:29.865
So get some of these loose themes start to find their point throughout Scripture, not only in that, but this praise.

13:31.789 --> 13:38.761
You remember when Jesus rides in his donkey in Jerusalem on Palm Sunday, the people are praising him, Hosanna, Hosanna, right?

13:39.322 --> 13:40.524
The praise in him has God.

13:41.446 --> 13:46.034
And what are the Pharisees of religious leaders of that day that get super uncomfortable with it, which makes sense?

13:46.178 --> 13:47.760
They don't know that Jesus has got himself.

13:47.781 --> 13:49.183
They don't know he's worthy of this praise.

13:49.243 --> 13:51.046
And they say, hey, man, have these people stop.

13:51.066 --> 13:51.907
And what does Jesus say?

13:51.927 --> 13:55.012
If I tell them to stop, the rocks are going to cry out.

13:56.013 --> 13:57.556
Like the creation knows who I am.

13:57.576 --> 13:59.239
They are here to praise me.

14:01.702 --> 14:05.288
He is worthy of praise as God himself.

14:06.650 --> 14:09.615
As a descendant of Judah, he is the fulfillment of this promise.

14:10.957 --> 14:14.162
On Palm Sunday, this is what we see the fulfillment of this.

14:14.530 --> 14:16.392
The brothers falling down and worship.

14:17.954 --> 14:24.823
As you see all the people on the street, worshiping Jesus, as he just rides into the town, this is the brothers bowing down.

14:26.345 --> 14:32.573
One from Judah's line being praised by all the other tribes being praised as God because he is God.

14:34.636 --> 14:42.386
Which means he's not coming to merely just to be praised, but to end corruption.

14:43.650 --> 14:50.959
He's worthy of the praise that we give him, which means he's capable of doing all the things that we praise him for, to right every wrong.

14:51.500 --> 14:55.024
He can actually carry the messianic promises because he is God himself.

14:55.064 --> 14:57.447
He cannot fail in his task.

14:57.487 --> 15:00.691
He has come to deliver us, to make all things new.

15:01.772 --> 15:04.275
And Jesus can do this because he's not merely a man.

15:05.016 --> 15:06.238
He's not just a great man.

15:06.638 --> 15:08.721
He's not just the best of man.

15:08.781 --> 15:10.483
He is the God man.

15:12.265 --> 15:12.946
The one who

15:13.058 --> 15:19.328
brought all things into being in creation, can recreate again because he has the power to do it.

15:20.330 --> 15:25.038
And this praise here shows us the nature of who he is, that he has got himself.

15:26.781 --> 15:30.927
It's the first thing we see here in this promise that Jesus is God.

15:32.049 --> 15:35.355
And this goes on to show us what kind of God he is.

15:35.415 --> 15:39.762
And next thing we see is kind of the strength and the scope of

15:40.066 --> 15:41.488
of who this God is.

15:41.528 --> 15:46.093
And this is the second thing we find that not only is Jesus God, but Jesus is the Lion King God.

15:47.896 --> 15:49.738
Jesus is the Lion King God.

15:49.758 --> 15:51.500
